Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels like in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on every tongue, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's about the environment and the climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and where we must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a driving role in the negotiation of the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
However, these measures, important as they are, are not sufficient to meet the challenges facing the world today.
The increasingly high temperatures could lead to the total disappearance of the Arctic ice sheet by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the victims of respiratory diseases are increasing as air pollution worsens.
We still have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's look at these people, growing in numbers every day, ready to take action to question their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families taking to the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also committing, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it's the policies and politicians, at the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let's make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be brought to zero by the middle of the century.
Together, we can invest massively in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transportation, as well as maritime and air commercial transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the leading continent in electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a true circular economy that minimizes waste.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four areas: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work today, for example, by launching a European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by eliminating plastics from our supply chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have declined by approximately 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations Biodiversity Conference, to be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and introduce an ambitious plan for the blue economy and marine preservation.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to support this green transition.
But these massive tasks ahead of us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is still the same – and most vulnerable – who are asked to bear the costs.
All measures must therefore be designed above all to minimize social costs.
And at the same time, we must start working today with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it is pointless to have strict European rules on pesticides or forestry management if our imported food and wood products are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three pillars could become the foundation of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in a severe ecological debt, and it would be more than justified for the stability and growth pact that applies to public finances of member states to have an equivalent for European green goals!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not be afraid to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and "extended producer responsibility" for products on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet the commitments made under the Paris Agreement.
This is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
And the EU's new budget and investment plan, leveraging private sector investments, could further enhance the Union's power to act.
The financial sector will play a crucial role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway's sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon".
Finally, although some member states may see this as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, as well as subsidies for fossil fuels. In short, on integrating sustainability into public spending.
Behind these projects, these initiatives, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must define ambitious goals and "missions" with both short-term and long-term resonance that have real social impact.
With member states and the European Parliament, we will need to determine a common roadmap and engage in in-depth discussions, just as we will with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to avoid the reality of our environment.
It's already very late to launch a European 'Green New Deal'. But it's not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
